## Deriving the Weak Form

::: {#ca2e8d3c .cell execution_count=3}
```` { .cell-code code-fold="true"}
```{{python}}
#| code-fold: true
weak_eq = fem.derive_weak_form()
```

````

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'><b>Step 1: Multiply the strong form by a test function v(x):</b></span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>EXPLANATION: We start with the strong form of our differential equation and multiply both sides by a test function v(x)</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>This is the first step in converting to the weak form.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'> The test function v(x) will eventually vanish at the boundaries, helping us incorporate boundary conditions naturally.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display .cell-output-markdown}
$\displaystyle \left(A{\left(x \right)} \frac{d^{2}}{d x^{2}} y{\left(x \right)} + B{\left(x \right)} \frac{d}{d x} y{\left(x \right)} + C{\left(x \right)} y{\left(x \right)}\right) v{\left(x \right)} = F{\left(x \right)} v{\left(x \right)}$
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'><b>Step 2: Integrate over the domain [0, L]:</b></span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>EXPLANATION:<br> We integrate both sides of the equation over the entire domain [0, L].</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'><br> This transforms our pointwise equation into an integral equation that will hold over the whole domain.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'> This step moves us from a local formulation to a global one, which is a key aspect of the finite element method.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display .cell-output-markdown}
$\displaystyle \int\limits_{0}^{L} \left(A{\left(x \right)} \frac{d^{2}}{d x^{2}} y{\left(x \right)} + B{\left(x \right)} \frac{d}{d x} y{\left(x \right)} + C{\left(x \right)} y{\left(x \right)}\right) v{\left(x \right)}\, dx = \int\limits_{0}^{L} F{\left(x \right)} v{\left(x \right)}\, dx$
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'><b>Step 3: Expand the left-hand side:</b></span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>EXPLANATION: </span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>We expand the left-hand side to separate the terms with different derivatives of y. <br> This makes it easier to apply integration by parts to the second-derivative term.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>Breaking down the differential operator allows us to handle each term appropriately based on the order of derivatives.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display .cell-output-markdown}
$\displaystyle \int\limits_{0}^{L} A{\left(x \right)} v{\left(x \right)} \frac{d^{2}}{d x^{2}} y{\left(x \right)}\, dx + \int\limits_{0}^{L} B{\left(x \right)} v{\left(x \right)} \frac{d}{d x} y{\left(x \right)}\, dx + \int\limits_{0}^{L} C{\left(x \right)} v{\left(x \right)} y{\left(x \right)}\, dx = \int\limits_{0}^{L} F{\left(x \right)} v{\left(x \right)}\, dx$
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'><b>Step 4: Integration by parts for the term with second derivative:</b></span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>EXPLANATION:<br> </span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>This is the critical step that reduces the order of derivatives in our equation. <br> We apply integration by parts to the term containing the second derivative of y.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'> The formula for integration by parts is:</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>  ∫u·dv = [u·v] - ∫v·du</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>For our case:<br></span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>  u = v(x)·A(x) and dv = d²y/dx² dx</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>  du = d(v(x)·A(x))/dx dx and v = dy/dx</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>Using the product rule:</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>  d/dx(v·A·dy/dx) = v·A·d²y/dx² + (v·A)'·dy/dx</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>Rearranging:</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>  v·A·d²y/dx² = d/dx(v·A·dy/dx) - (v·A)'·dy/dx</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>This substitution allows us to replace the second derivative with first derivatives, reducing the continuity requirements on our approximation functions.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>After integration by parts:</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display .cell-output-markdown}
$\displaystyle \int\limits_{0}^{L} A{\left(x \right)} v{\left(x \right)} \frac{d^{2}}{d x^{2}} y{\left(x \right)}\, dx = - A{\left(0 \right)} v{\left(0 \right)} \left. \frac{d}{d x} y{\left(x \right)} \right|_{\substack{ x=0 }} + A{\left(L \right)} v{\left(L \right)} \frac{d}{d L} y{\left(L \right)} - \int\limits_{0}^{L} \left(A{\left(x \right)} \frac{d}{d x} v{\left(x \right)} + v{\left(x \right)} \frac{d}{d x} A{\left(x \right)}\right) \frac{d}{d x} y{\left(x \right)}\, dx$
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'><b>Step 5: Apply boundary conditions v(0) = v(L) = 0:</b></span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>EXPLANATION: </span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>We choose our test functions v(x) to vanish at the domain boundaries <br>(v(0) = v(L) = 0). </span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>This is a crucial step that eliminates the boundary terms from integration by parts. <br> By carefully selecting test functions that satisfy these conditions, we naturally incorporate the essential (Dirichlet) boundary conditions into our formulation.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'> This is one of the elegant aspects of the finite element method.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>The boundary term [v·A·dy/dx]₀ᴸ vanishes because v(0) = v(L) = 0.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'><b>Step 6: Assemble the final weak form:</b></span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>EXPLANATION: <br> Now we collect all terms to form the complete weak formulation.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>This form requires lower continuity requirements on our solution (only first derivatives appear).</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'> The weak form is equivalent to the strong form for sufficiently smooth solutions, but it allows us to find approximate solutions with less smoothness.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>This is the foundation for the finite element approximation where we'll represent the solution as a combination of piecewise polynomial functions.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display .cell-output-markdown}
$\displaystyle - \int\limits_{0}^{L} \left(A{\left(x \right)} \frac{d}{d x} v{\left(x \right)} + v{\left(x \right)} \frac{d}{d x} A{\left(x \right)}\right) \frac{d}{d x} y{\left(x \right)}\, dx + \int\limits_{0}^{L} B{\left(x \right)} v{\left(x \right)} \frac{d}{d x} y{\left(x \right)}\, dx + \int\limits_{0}^{L} C{\left(x \right)} v{\left(x \right)} y{\left(x \right)}\, dx = \int\limits_{0}^{L} F{\left(x \right)} v{\left(x \right)}\, dx$
:::
:::


## Shape Functions for Discretization

::: {#e652cd5c .cell execution_count=4}
```` { .cell-code code-fold="true"}
```{{python}}
#| code-fold: true
N = 5
phi, a, b, y_approx, v_approx = fem.define_shape_functions(N)
```

````

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'><b>Step 7: Define shape functions for N elements:</b><br></span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>EXPLANATION: <br></span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>Now we discretize the problem by representing both the solution y(x) and test function v(x) as linear combinations of shape functions. </span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>This transforms our continuous problem into a discrete one with a finite number of unknowns (the coefficients).</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>The shape functions are typically chosen to be simple piecewise polynomials (often linear) that are non-zero only over a small portion of the domain .</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>This 'local support' property often leads to sparse matrices in the final system.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display .cell-output-markdown}
$\displaystyle \left[ \phi_{1}{\left(x \right)}, \  \phi_{2}{\left(x \right)}, \  \phi_{3}{\left(x \right)}, \  \phi_{4}{\left(x \right)}, \  \phi_{5}{\left(x \right)}\right]$
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'><b>Step 8: Express solution and test functions using shape functions:</b></span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>EXPLANATION:<br> </span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>We approximate both the solution y(x) and test function v(x) using the same set of shape functions. </span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>The solution is written as a sum of shape functions with unknown coefficients a_j. <br> Similarly, the test function is written as a sum with coefficients b_i.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>This is the Galerkin approach, where we use the same functions for both approximation and testing.</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display .cell-output-markdown}
$\displaystyle y{\left(x \right)} = a_{1} \phi_{1}{\left(x \right)} + a_{2} \phi_{2}{\left(x \right)} + a_{3} \phi_{3}{\left(x \right)} + a_{4} \phi_{4}{\left(x \right)} + a_{5} \phi_{5}{\left(x \right)}$
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display .cell-output-markdown}
$\displaystyle v{\left(x \right)} = b_{1} \phi_{1}{\left(x \right)} + b_{2} \phi_{2}{\left(x \right)} + b_{3} \phi_{3}{\left(x \right)} + b_{4} \phi_{4}{\left(x \right)} + b_{5} \phi_{5}{\left(x \right)}$
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>
Where:<br></span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>- aⱼ are unknown constants we need to solve for </span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>- bᵢ are arbitrary constants for the test function</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>- φᵢ(x), φⱼ(x) are known shape functions (typically piecewise linear functions)</span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>NOTE: In the finite element method, we often choose shape functions that are equal to 1 at their corresponding node and 0 at all other nodes.<br></span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'> This makes it easy to enforce boundary conditions and interpret the coefficients aⱼ as the solution values at the nodes.</span>
```
:::
:::


## Assembling the FEM System

::: {#b240f5a8 .cell execution_count=5}
```` { .cell-code code-fold="true"}
```{{python}}
#| code-fold: true
K, F_vec = fem.assemble_fem_system(weak_eq, phi, a, b, y_approx, v_approx, N)
```

````

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'><b> Step 9: Substitute discretized functions into the weak form:</b></span>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<br>
```
:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<span style='font-size: 30px;'>EXPLANATION:<br> We now substitute our approximations for y(x) and v(x) into the weak form.</span>
```
